# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: declarative-shadow-dom
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] The **`ShadowRoot`** interface of the Shadow DOM API is the root node of a DOM subtree that is rendered separately from a document's main DOM tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] You can retrieve a reference to an element's shadow root using its `Element.shadowRoot` property, provided it was created using `Element.attachShadow()` with the `mode` option set to `open`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` within the shadow tree that has focus.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Add an array of constructed stylesheets to be used by the shadow DOM subtree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] These may be shared with other DOM subtrees that share the same parent `Document` node, and the document itself.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root is clonable.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns the `CustomElementRegistry` object associated with this shadow root, or `null` if one has not been set.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root delegates focus if a non-focusable node is selected.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] The element that's currently in full screen mode for this shadow tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns a reference to the DOM element the `ShadowRoot` is attached to.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Sets or returns a reference to the DOM tree inside the `ShadowRoot`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] The mode of the `ShadowRoot`, either `open` or `closed`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] This defines whether or not the shadow root's internal features are accessible from JavaScript.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` within the shadow tree that is currently being presented in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` set as the target for mouse events while the pointer is locked.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] `null` if lock is pending, pointer is unlocked, or if the target is in another tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] A nullable string value that indicates the effective target of any element reference made against the shadow host from outside the host element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] The value should be the ID of an element inside the shadow DOM.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] If set, target references to the host element from outside the shadow DOM will cause the referenced target element to become the effective target of the reference to the host element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root is serializable.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] A serializable shadow root inside an element will be serialized by `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` when its `options.serializableShadowRoots` parameter is set `true`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] This is set when the shadow root is created.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns a string containing the type of slot assignment, either `manual` or `named`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns a `StyleSheetList` of `CSSStyleSheet` objects for stylesheets explicitly linked into, or embedded in a shadow tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns an array of all `Animation` objects currently in effect, whose target elements are descendants of the shadow tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns a `Selection` object representing the range of text selected by the user, or the current position of the caret.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns the topmost element at the specified coordinates.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Returns an array of all elements at the specified coordinates.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Provides an XSS-safe method to parse and sanitize a string of HTML into a `DocumentFragment`, which then replaces the existing tree in the shadow DOM.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Parses a string of HTML into a document fragment, without sanitization, which then replaces the shadowroot's original subtree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] The HTML string may include declarative shadow roots, which would be parsed as template elements the HTML was set using `ShadowRoot.innerHTML`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] An event fired when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] The following snippets are taken from our life-cycle-callbacks example (see it live also), which creates an element that displays a square of a size and color specified in the element's attributes.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] Inside the `<custom-square>` element's class definition we include some life cycle callbacks that make a call to an external function, `updateStyle()`, which actually applies the size and color to the element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] You'll see that we are passing it `this` (the custom element itself) as a parameter.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/api-shadowroot] In the `updateStyle()` function itself, we get a reference to the shadow DOM using `Element.shadowRoot`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The **`attachShadow()`** method of the `Element` interface attaches a shadow DOM tree to the specified element and returns a reference to its `ShadowRoot`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A string specifying the *encapsulation mode* for the shadow DOM tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Elements inside the shadow root are accessible from JavaScript via the element's `shadowRoot` property.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Elements inside the shadow root cannot be accessed from JavaScript via the `shadowRoot` property, which is set to `null`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A boolean that specifies whether the shadow root is clonable: when set to `true`, the shadow host cloned with `Node.cloneNode()` or `Document.importNode()` will include shadow root in the copy.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A `CustomElementRegistry` that will be used as the scoped custom element registry of the attached shadow root.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] If `null` or `undefined`, the shadow root will use the global registry referenced by `Window.customElements`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A boolean that, when set to `true`, specifies behavior that mitigates custom element issues around focusability.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] When a non-focusable part of the shadow DOM is clicked, the first focusable part is given focus, and the shadow host is given any available `:focus` styling.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A string value that indicates the effective target of any element reference made against the shadow host from outside the host element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A boolean that, when set to `true`, indicates that the shadow root is serializable.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] If set, the shadow root may be serialized by calling the `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` methods with the `options.serializableShadowRoots` parameter set `true`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A string specifying the *slot assignment mode* for the shadow DOM tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Elements are automatically assigned to `<slot>` elements within this shadow root.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Any top-level children of the host with a `slot` attribute which matches the `name` attribute of a `<slot>` within this shadow root will be assigned to that slot.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Any top-level children of the host with no `slot` attribute will be assigned to the first `<slot>` with no `name` attribute (the "default slot"), if one is present.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Elements are manually assigned to particular slot elements using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The **`Element.attachShadow()`** method attaches a shadow DOM tree to the specified element and returns a reference to its `ShadowRoot`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] This is the programmatic mechanism to create a `ShadowRoot`, which is the root node of a Shadow DOM attached to a host element (it is also possible to create a `ShadowRoot` declaratively using the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the `<template>` element).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] It is used for creating custom elements.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Note that you can't attach a shadow root to every type of element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] There are some that can't have a shadow DOM for security reasons (for example `<a>`).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The method may be called on an element that already has a declarative shadow root, provided the specified mode `mode` matches the existing mode.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] In this case the `ShadowRoot` that was already present will be cleared and returned.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] This allows for cases where, for example, server-side rendering has already declaratively created a shadow root, and then client-side code attempts to attach the root again.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Otherwise calling `attachShadow()` on an element that already has a shadow root will throw an exception.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] A shadow root can be attached with an encapsulation mode, which is specified as either `open` or `closed`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] If the `{mode: "open"}` argument is passed, the host element's `shadowRoot` property can subsequently be used to get the attached shadow root.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] If `{mode: "closed"}` is passed then the Element's `shadowRoot` property is set to `null`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Note that JavaScript can still access a closed shadow root by storing the value returned by the function.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The following example is taken from our word-count-web-component demo (see it live also).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] You can see that we use `attachShadow()` in the middle of the code to create a shadow root, which we then attach our custom element's contents to.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] If the element has a static property named `disabledFeatures`, which is an array containing the string `"shadow"`, then the `attachShadow()` call will throw an exception.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] This example demonstrates named slot assignment.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] This code creates a web component that has three named slots for an article's title, metadata, and body section.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The `ShadowRoot` is attached in the custom element's constructor.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] We don't need to explicitly set the option `slotAssignment: "named"` because it is the default.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The HTML below uses the `<my-article>` web component we just created.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The nested elements are rendered in the component's slots based on name matching.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The unnamed elements are rendered in the component's unnamed slot (the body).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The example below should show the content of the slots displayed in the appropriate sections.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] This example demonstrates manual slot assignment.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] With this approach, each element must be manually assigned to a particular slot using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] There is no default assignment, so any slot that is not assigned will be empty.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] First we have a hidden support warning, displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support `slotAssignment: "manual"`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Next, we define our `<my-article>` custom element with child elements for the title, metadata, and body content.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Each child is identified by `id`; unlike named slot assignment, no `slot` attribute is needed.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The custom element attaches a shadow root with `slotAssignment: "manual"`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The shadow DOM contains unnamed slots identified by `id`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] The `assignSlots()` method manually assigns the light DOM elements to the slots.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] Note that multiple nodes can be assigned to a single slot — the order they are specified controls the render order.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/attachshadow] This code tests if the `ShadowRoot.slotAssignment` property is defined, and displays the warning if it is not.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] It’s been available across browsers since November 2015.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The **`<template>`** HTML element serves as a mechanism for holding HTML fragments, which can either be used later via JavaScript or generated immediately into shadow DOM.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Creates a shadow root for the parent element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] It is a declarative version of the `Element.attachShadow()` method and accepts the same enumerated values.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Exposes the internal shadow root DOM for JavaScript (recommended for most use cases).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Hides the internal shadow root DOM from JavaScript.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Sets the value of the `clonable` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] If set, a clone of the shadow host (the parent element of this `<template>`) created with `Node.cloneNode()` or `Document.importNode()` will include a shadow root in the copy.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Sets the `customElementRegistry` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `null`, rather than the document's custom element registry.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This allows a scoped `CustomElementRegistry` to be attached later using `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Sets the value of the `delegatesFocus` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] If this is set and a non-focusable element in the shadow tree is selected, then focus is delegated to the first focusable element in the tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Sets the value of the `referenceTarget` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Sets the value of the `serializable` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Sets the `slotAssignment` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This is the declarative equivalent of the `slotAssignment` option of the `Element.attachShadow()` method.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Elements with the `slot` attribute are assigned to the first `<slot>` in the template that has the corresponding `name` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] If multiple elements specify the same slot name, they are all added to the first slot in the template that has that name, and rendered in the order they are declared.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] All unnamed elements — elements that don't specify a `slot` attribute — are assigned to the default slot in the order they are declared.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This is the first unnamed `<slot>` in the template.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This element has no permitted content, because everything nested inside it in the HTML source does not actually become the children of the `<template>` element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The `Node.childNodes` property of the `<template>` element is always empty, and you can only access said nested content via the special `content` property.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] However, if you call `Node.appendChild()` or similar methods on the `<template>` element, then you would be inserting children into the `<template>` element itself, which is a violation of its content model and does not actually update the `DocumentFragment` returned by the `content` property.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Due to the way the `<template>` element is parsed, all `<html>`, `<head>`, and `<body>` opening and closing tags inside the template are syntax errors and are ignored by the parser, so `<template><head><title>Test</title></head></template>` is the same as `<template><title>Test</title></template>`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] There are two main ways to use the `<template>` element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] By default, the element's content is not rendered.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The corresponding `HTMLTemplateElement` interface includes a standard `content` property (without an equivalent content/markup attribute).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This `content` property is read-only and holds a `DocumentFragment` that contains the DOM subtree represented by the template.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The `Node.cloneNode()` and `Document.importNode()` methods both create a copy of a node.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The difference is that `importNode()` clones the node in the context of the calling document, whereas `cloneNode()` uses the document of the node being cloned.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The document context determines the `CustomElementRegistry` for constructing any custom elements.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] For this reason, use `document.importNode()` to clone the `content` fragment so that custom element descendants are constructed using the definitions in the current document, rather than the separate document that owns the template content.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] See the `Node.cloneNode()` page's examples for more details.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Note that the `DocumentFragment` container itself should not have data attached to it.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] See the Data on the DocumentFragment is not cloned example for more details.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] If the `<template>` element contains the `shadowrootmode` attribute with a value of either `open` or `closed`, the HTML parser will immediately generate a shadow DOM.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The element is replaced in the DOM by its content wrapped in a `ShadowRoot`, which is attached to the parent element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This is the declarative equivalent of calling `Element.attachShadow()` to attach a shadow root to an element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] If the element has any other value for `shadowrootmode`, or does not have the `shadowrootmode` attribute, the parser generates a `HTMLTemplateElement`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Similarly, if there are multiple declarative shadow roots, only the first one is replaced by a `ShadowRoot` — subsequent instances are parsed as `HTMLTemplateElement` objects.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Other attributes prefixed with `shadowroot` allow declarative customization of the `ShadowRoot`, such as controlling how slots are assigned.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] First we start with the HTML portion of the example.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] First, we have a table into which we will later insert content using JavaScript code.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Then comes the template, which describes the structure of an HTML fragment representing a single table row.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Now that the table has been created and the template defined, we use JavaScript to insert rows into the table, with each row being constructed using the template as its basis.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] In this example, a hidden support warning is included at the beginning of the markup.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Next, there are two `<article>` elements, each containing nested `<style>` elements with different behaviors.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The first `<style>` element is global to the whole document.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The second one is scoped to the shadow root generated in place of the `<template>` element because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This example demonstrates how `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` is applied to a shadow root that is created declaratively, and the effect this has on focus.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The code first declares a shadow root inside a `<div>` element, using the `<template>` element with the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This displays both a non-focusable `<div>` containing text and a focusable `<input>` element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] It also uses CSS to style elements with `:focus` to blue, and to set the normal styling of the host element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The second code block is identical except that it sets the `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` attribute, which delegates focus to the first focusable element in the tree if a non-focusable element in the tree is selected.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Last of all we use the following CSS to apply a red border to the parent `<div>` element when it has focus.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] When the HTML is first rendered, the elements have no styling, as shown in the first image.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] For the shadow root that does not have `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` set you can click anywhere except the `<input>` and the focus does not change (if you select the `<input>` element it will look like the second image).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] For the shadow root with `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` set, clicking on the text (which is non-focusable) selects the `<input>` element, as this is the first focusable element in the tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This also focuses the parent element as shown below.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM based on their `slot` attribute (matched against the slot's `name` attribute).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] First we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The article contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] We don't need to set its `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute because named slot assignment is the default.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The template defines elements that have named slots for "header" and "meta" information, and an unnamed slot for "body" information.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The elements are styled differently so it is easy to differentiate them.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Inside the same host, below the template, we have four elements for populating the slots.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The `<span>` elements have `slot` attributes that match the `name` attributes on slots in the template, and will populate the corresponding slots.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The two `<p>` elements are unnamed, so are both inserted into the unnamed `<slot>` in the "body" element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM using manual slot assignment.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] With this approach, each element must manually be assigned to a particular slot.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Next, we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] This contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute, and will use manual slot assignment because `shadowrootslotassignment="manual"` is set.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The template defines elements that have slots for "header", "meta", and "body" information, that can be separately referenced by their `id` attribute.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The JavaScript for manual slot assignment is shown below.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] First the code gets the slots within the shadow root, then the text to be inserted, and finally assigns the text to the slot.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Note that you can only assign a node once to any particular slot, and that if you assign multiple nodes to a single slot using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`, the order they are specified controls the order they are added.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] The code displays the hidden support warning if slot assignment is not supported.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] When a `DocumentFragment` value is passed, `Node.appendChild` and similar methods move only the *child nodes* of that value into the target node.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Therefore, it is usually preferable to attach event handlers to the children of a `DocumentFragment`, rather than to the `DocumentFragment` itself.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] Since `firstClone` is a `DocumentFragment`, only its children are added to `container` when `appendChild` is called; the event handlers of `firstClone` are not copied.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/elements-template] In contrast, because an event handler is added to the first *child node* of `secondClone`, the event handler is copied when `appendChild` is called, and clicking on it works as one would expect.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/server-side-scripting] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowroot-mode] The **`mode`** read-only property of the `ShadowRoot` specifies its mode — either `open` or `closed`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowroot-mode] When the `mode` of a shadow root is `"closed"`, the shadow root's implementation internals are inaccessible and unchangeable from JavaScript—in the same way the implementation internals of, for example, the `<video>` element are inaccessible and unchangeable from JavaScript.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowroot-mode] The property value is set using the `mode` property of the object passed to `Element.attachShadow()`, or using the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the `<template>` element when a shadow root is created declaratively.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowroot-mode] Elements of the shadow root are accessible from JavaScript outside the root.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowroot-mode] Nodes inside the closed shadow tree cannot be accessed by JavaScript outside of the root.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowrootmode] Since February 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowrootmode] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowrootmode] The **`shadowRootMode`** property of the `HTMLTemplateElement` interface reflects the value of the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/shadowrootmode] Reflects the value of the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:declarative-shadow-dom/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
